# PRAXIS Shared Quality Standards

## Commits, Reviews & GitLab
- Use conventional commits (feat, fix, chore, docs, refactor, test) with `#<issue>` references.
- Every MR requires at least one peer review before merge; use `review-and-ship` or `make-pr-easy-to-review` skill on every significant change.
- Prefer small, focused MRs with clear purpose and updated descriptions when behavior changes.
- All code must pass lint/type checks; fix issues before requesting review.

## TypeScript & Code Style (applies to any TS/JS)
- Use exhaustive switch handling for unions/enums with `never` default check.
- Keep imports at top of file; no inline imports except for documented circular-dependency cases.
- Error handling must preserve provenance (link back to source log lines or data contracts).

## General Project Practices
- Daily 15-min syncs; document decisions in MRs or daily notes.
- Provenance and confidence rationale visible in all UI and outputs for interview storytelling.
- Use existing Cursor skills (review-bugbot, review-security, canvas for wireframes) proactively.
- No global Cursor setting changes; all project config lives in this `.cursor/rules/` for team onboarding.
- Before dev work or MRs, sync with GitLab `main` per `praxis-git-sync.mdc` or run `/sync-with-main`.